fcitx5-sinsebeolsik-p2 (0.1.5) unstable; urgency=medium

  * INT5 (Muhenkan) passthrough modifier: when the host sends INT5 down,
    the engine bypasses P2 automaton for all subsequent keys until INT5
    up. This lets keyboards (e.g. ZMK on Totem) wrap symbol-layer keys
    with INT5 down/up to type `;`, `'`, `/`, `"`, `:` while the IME is
    active without jamo interception, preserving normal P2 input on
    bare keys. The in-progress syllable is flushed on the first INT5
    press so passthrough output cannot bleed into the composition
    buffer, and `int5_held` is reset on activate / deactivate / reset
    to prevent stuck state across focus loss or IME toggles. 178/178
    tests still pass (no behavior change for non-INT5 paths);
    integration validated via uinput simulation and the real ZMK
    firmware on Canary noangle layout.

 -- Bogamie <bogamie02@gmail.com>  Tue, 05 May 2026 00:00:00 +0900

fcitx5-sinsebeolsik-p2 (0.1.4) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Backspace correctness for real-jung syllables: fixed spurious revert to
    virtual jung when removing a jong from a syllable whose jung was placed
    directly as a real vowel (e.g. jvf → 옾 → BS now stays at 오 then re-
    composes to 옾 on next f, instead of collapsing to 와). Tracked via a
    new jung_was_virtual flag so only freezes that actually happened at
    apply_jong time get reverted on backspace; jof → 웊 → BS → 우(virtual)
    → c → 웨 path is unchanged. 178/178 tests.

 -- Bogamie <bogamie02@gmail.com>  Mon, 04 May 2026 00:00:00 +0900

fcitx5-sinsebeolsik-p2 (0.1.3) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Yet-Hangul ㆍ (araea) input: full automaton support for jung F/FI/FF
    with conjoining-jamo rendering (precomposed syllables don't exist for
    these). z key now produces real jung F under D&&!E or virtual ㆍ;
    Z (shift) unified to jung=F so Z standalone yields ㆍ and jZ yields
    ᄋᆞ in one syllable. Backspace decomposes FI/FF and restores virtual
    ㆍ for re-composition.
  * Wayland compatibility fixes: (1) reset() no longer commits the
    in-progress syllable — matches fcitx5-hangul policy and avoids
    stray glyphs at the new cursor on focus changes. (2) Shift detection
    now reads rawKey().states() instead of normalized key.states() so
    Wayland's xkb-level modifier consumption doesn't drop the Shift bit
    before the qwerty translator sees it. (3) Literal-text commits now
    coalesce flush+literal into a single commitString call to work
    around Wayland frame coalescing that drops the earlier commit.
  * Cluster correctness: jong+jong without an in-progress cho no longer
    cluster (qq=ㅅㅅ now matches the simulator instead of producing ㅆ).
  * ":" (Shift+;) added as explicit literal so non-QWERTY system layouts
    (Canary, Dvorak, …) emit ':' regardless of host xkb routing.
  * README simplified: install-first flow with the .deb path up top.

 -- Bogamie <bogamie02@gmail.com>  Sat, 02 May 2026 18:00:00 +0900

fcitx5-sinsebeolsik-p2 (0.1.2) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Backspace polish: preserve single-key jongs, restore frozen virtual
    jung after jong/jung removal so re-pressing the same vowel re-composes
    (e.g. joc → 웨 → BS → 우(virtual ㅜ) → f → 웊).
  * Right-hand symbol layer: shifted right-hand keys (H/J/K/L/M/N/U/Y/P,
    Shift+', Shift+Z) emit literal codepoints (□ ' " · … ― ; ○ × / ㆍ)
    per the .ist simulator spec. Shift+I/O are absorbed (empty slot).
  * Internal QWERTY re-translation via libxkbcommon: engine now keeps its
    own xkb_state with a US QWERTY keymap and re-evaluates each printable
    keystroke's hardware keycode through it before keymap.toml lookup, so
    the IME works correctly on hosts using non-QWERTY system XKB layouts
    (Canary, Dvorak, Colemak, …). Falls back to original keysym if
    libxkbcommon initialization fails — QWERTY hosts behave identically.
  * Engine cosmetic: tray label 신P2 → 한, monochrome icon name.

 -- Bogamie <bogamie02@gmail.com>  Sat, 02 May 2026 02:15:00 +0900

